            <Title>Authority</Title>
            <Text>What it is
People are more willing to believe a statement when it comes from someone they believe is an expert on the matter being discussed. They also are more likely to go along with an authority figure’s actions, even when they begin to realize the actions are inappropriate or simply wrong.
How it relates to investing
Many new investors haven’t developed a solid grasp of the investing process and tend to assume that stockbrokers and those business “experts” who frequently appear in the media understand the topic better than they do. This can lead them to accept investment recommendations that are not based on solid research—or be swayed to enter the market at the peak of a cycle (a mistake often compounded when they decide to sell at the bottom of the cycle).
Most viewers believe that the correspondents or anchors of various business news programs are experts, even though it’s rare that they are. Because they are seen as authorities on matters concerning investing, this often gives more weight to their thoughts on the market (or individual companies) than is warranted. The truth is, while most of the interviewers and commentators on these shows are trained in journalism, many of them have only a rudimentary grasp of investing. Writers for the various financial print publications also should be viewed with a healthy dose of skepticism—at least initially. I have managed to find several who write very comprehensive and enlightening articles. Carol Loomis at Fortune and Bethany McLean of Vanity Fair are two such writers.
#
